#import "/lib/prelude.typ": *
#show: chapter.with(title: "Iteration Expressions")

SSA is a useful IR because it enables complex, 
whole-procedure transformation of code, 
but its block-statement-value hierarchy 
makes it difficult to uniformly formulate the allowed transformations 
as an (in)equational theory. 
Instead, therefore, we will start by studying a simple, 
first-order language of expressions, 
#liter,
equipped with an _iteration operator_
--
we will then show that this language is _equivalent_ to SSA,
and therefore we'll be able to use it as a tool to more effectively
give a sound and complete equational, and later refinement, theory for SSA.

= Syntax

#liter is a standard first-order expression language with branching and
iteration: a functional analogue of #msc[Imp]~@winskel1993.
Its grammar is parametrized by a set of _base types_ $X âˆˆ cal(X)$
and a set of _instructions_ $f âˆˆ cal(I)$.
To model multiple arguments and control flow,
our grammar of types $A, B, C$ includes all _tensor products_ $A tytensor B$
and _coproducts_ $A tysum B$ generated by base types $X$,
along with a _unit type_ $tyunit$ and an _empty type_ $tyempty$.
Mirroring this, expressions $a, b, c$ consist of

- _Variables_ $x, y, z$

- _Applications_ $f med a$, consisting of instructions $f âˆˆ cal(I)$
  applied to an expression $a$

- _Let-bindings_ $#letx($x$, $a$, $b$)$ 
  and _destructuring let-bindings_ $#letx($(x, y)$, $a$, $b$)$. 
  
  We write $a seq b$ as syntactic sugar for
  $#letx($Â·$, $a$, $b$)$ 
  (i.e., a let-binding where the bound variable is not used in $b$).

- _Case-expressions_ $#casex($e$, $x$, $a$, $y$, $b$)$,
  representing branching control-flow

- _Iteration-expressions_ $#iterx($a$, $x$, $b$)$, representing a variant of
  _tail-controlled loop_, which:

  - Evaluates an initial value $a : A$

  - Evaluates the loop body $b : B tysum A$ with $x = a$;
    if the loop evaluates to a value of type $B$, we return it,
    otherwise, we re-evaluate the loop with $x$ having the new value of type $A$

We give the full grammar for #liter types, expressions, and
contexts in @fig-expr-syntax.

